<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-11-11T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-11-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="1022" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1022">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 412.00/37.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Brazilian Minister</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Brazilian Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-11-11">
                                    <hi rend="italic">November 11, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>203. Carranza issued regulations through War Office, which have now been
                            communicated to the Diplomatic Corps, to the effect— <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>That for the better investigation of facts relative to claims
                                    presented by foreigners it is desirable to require them to prove
                                    their nationality as well as their lawful ownership of property
                                    claimed.</p>
                            </quote>
                        </p>
                        <p>I am under the impression that such exaction can not be admitted, because
                            such proof can be investigated only by the ministers or consuls. Their
                            statement to that is and should be accepted as conclusive. However, I
                            would like to know Department’s views before answering.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Cardoso de Oliveira</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>